<subSubSection id="35F00DF1F334965BFF4BFC9EFC538672" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="1171" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170" type="description">
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF3349658FF4BFC9EFD6087DB" blockId="1.[178,1085,857,909]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">
R e d e s c r i p t i o n: Body of small size, body length 
<quantity id="BA12F39FF3349658FCFBFC9DFC928738" box="[770,891,857,879]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.15" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170" unit="mm" value="3.15" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="2.8">2.8-3.5 mm</quantity>
. Habitus similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="BAEA25F9F3349658FF03FCB3FE0B87DA" authority="STEPHENS 1829" authorityName="STEPHENS" authorityYear="1829" box="[250,482,887,909]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F3349658FF03FCB3FED487DB" box="[250,317,887,908]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Sunius</emphasis>
STEPHENS 1829
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F3349658FDEAFCB3FD6A87DB" box="[531,643,887,908]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Neosclerus</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF3349658FF4BFC58FBC780CB" blockId="1.[178,1085,924,1180]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">
Head with coarse and dense punctation (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FDA9FC58FD7B87E5" box="[592,658,924,946]" captionStart="Figs 1-4" captionStartId="2.[178,218,1543,1565]" captionTargetBox="[180,1081,927,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-296@2.[178,1085,927,1534]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-4: Eusclerus rugifrons SHARP, holotype: (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median dorsal portion of pronotum. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2: 0.5 mm; 3-4: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326081" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326081/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FD67FC58FD4587E5" box="[670,684,924,946]" captionStart="Figs 5-11" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1409,1431]" captionTargetBox="[185,1080,212,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-65@4.[178,1085,212,1392]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5-11: Eusclerus sordidus SHARP, holotype: (5) habitus; (6) forebody; (7) median dorsal portion of head; (8) median dorsal portion of pronotum; (9) male sternite VIII; (10-11) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 5: 1.0 mm; 6: 0.5 mm; 7-9: 0.2 mm; 10-11: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326085/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">8</figureCitation>
). Eyes conspicuously large (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FC2AFC58FBFC87E5" box="[979,1045,924,946]" captionStart="Figs 1-4" captionStartId="2.[178,218,1543,1565]" captionTargetBox="[180,1081,927,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-296@2.[178,1085,927,1534]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-4: Eusclerus rugifrons SHARP, holotype: (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median dorsal portion of pronotum. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2: 0.5 mm; 3-4: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326081" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326081/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FBD8FC58FBD987E5" box="[1057,1072,924,946]" captionStart="Figs 5-11" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1409,1431]" captionTargetBox="[185,1080,212,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-65@4.[178,1085,212,1392]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5-11: Eusclerus sordidus SHARP, holotype: (5) habitus; (6) forebody; (7) median dorsal portion of head; (8) median dorsal portion of pronotum; (9) male sternite VIII; (10-11) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 5: 1.0 mm; 6: 0.5 mm; 7-9: 0.2 mm; 10-11: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326085/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">6</figureCitation>
). Neck broad, slightly less than half as broad as maximal head width (including eyes). Gular sutures narrowly separated, distance between sutures in the middle subequal to width of antennomere III. Antenna of similar morphology as that of 
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F3349658FC3FFC30FBE0805E" box="[966,1033,1012,1033]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Sunius</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F3349658FF4BFBD5FECB8071" box="[178,290,1041,1062]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Neosclerus</emphasis>
. Mandibles moderately slender and with three distinct molar teeth (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FC1AFBD5FBDB8070" box="[995,1074,1041,1063]" captionStart="Figs 21-28" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1171,1193]" captionTargetBox="[183,1081,220,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-198@7.[178,1085,212,1156]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 21-28: Sciocharis buphthalma SCHEERPELTZ (21-24) and Eusclerus sordidus SHARP (25-28): (21, 27) labium; (22, 28) ligula; (23) male sternite VII; (24) male sternite VIII; (25) mandibles; (26) labrum. Scale bars: 23-25: 0.2 mm; 21, 26-27: 0.1 mm; 22, 28: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326091" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326091/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). Labrum distinctly transverse; anterior margin notched in the middle, without distinct teeth on either side of this notch (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FDE8FB8FFDB68036" box="[529,607,1099,1121]" captionStart="Figs 21-28" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1171,1193]" captionTargetBox="[183,1081,220,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-198@7.[178,1085,212,1156]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 21-28: Sciocharis buphthalma SCHEERPELTZ (21-24) and Eusclerus sordidus SHARP (25-28): (21, 27) labium; (22, 28) ligula; (23) male sternite VII; (24) male sternite VIII; (25) mandibles; (26) labrum. Scale bars: 23-25: 0.2 mm; 21, 26-27: 0.1 mm; 22, 28: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326091" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326091/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Maxillary palpus four-jointed; palpomere III 2-2.5 times as long as broad, much larger than palpomeres I-II; palpomere IV fine, short, and needle-shaped. Labial palpus three-jointed (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FD7BFB42FD2280CB" box="[642,715,1158,1180]" captionStart="Figs 21-28" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1171,1193]" captionTargetBox="[183,1081,220,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-198@7.[178,1085,212,1156]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 21-28: Sciocharis buphthalma SCHEERPELTZ (21-24) and Eusclerus sordidus SHARP (25-28): (21, 27) labium; (22, 28) ligula; (23) male sternite VII; (24) male sternite VIII; (25) mandibles; (26) labrum. Scale bars: 23-25: 0.2 mm; 21, 26-27: 0.1 mm; 22, 28: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326091" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326091/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
); ligula with 12 stout setae (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FC20FB42FBCB80CB" box="[985,1058,1158,1180]" captionStart="Figs 21-28" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1171,1193]" captionTargetBox="[183,1081,220,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-198@7.[178,1085,212,1156]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 21-28: Sciocharis buphthalma SCHEERPELTZ (21-24) and Eusclerus sordidus SHARP (25-28): (21, 27) labium; (22, 28) ligula; (23) male sternite VII; (24) male sternite VIII; (25) mandibles; (26) labrum. Scale bars: 23-25: 0.2 mm; 21, 26-27: 0.1 mm; 22, 28: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326091" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326091/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF3349658FF4BFB68FDE28161" blockId="1.[178,1085,1195,1334]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">
Pronotum approximately as wide as long and somewhat narrower than head (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FC29FB6FFBFA8096" box="[976,1043,1195,1217]" captionStart="Figs 1-4" captionStartId="2.[178,218,1543,1565]" captionTargetBox="[180,1081,927,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-296@2.[178,1085,927,1534]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-4: Eusclerus rugifrons SHARP, holotype: (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median dorsal portion of pronotum. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2: 0.5 mm; 3-4: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326081" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326081/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FBD8FB6FFBD98096" box="[1057,1072,1195,1217]" captionStart="Figs 5-11" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1409,1431]" captionTargetBox="[185,1080,212,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-65@4.[178,1085,212,1392]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5-11: Eusclerus sordidus SHARP, holotype: (5) habitus; (6) forebody; (7) median dorsal portion of head; (8) median dorsal portion of pronotum; (9) male sternite VIII; (10-11) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 5: 1.0 mm; 6: 0.5 mm; 7-9: 0.2 mm; 10-11: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326085/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">6</figureCitation>
); punctation dense and granulose; midline posteriorly with narrow impunctate band (
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FBE9FB0DFF2880AB" captionStart="Figs 1-4" captionStartId="2.[178,218,1543,1565]" captionTargetBox="[180,1081,927,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-296@2.[178,1085,927,1534]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-4: Eusclerus rugifrons SHARP, holotype: (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median dorsal portion of pronotum. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2: 0.5 mm; 3-4: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326081" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326081/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Figs 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E5D142FFF3349658FF37FB22FF3580AB" box="[206,220,1254,1276]" captionStart="Figs 5-11" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1409,1431]" captionTargetBox="[185,1080,212,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-65@4.[178,1085,212,1392]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5-11: Eusclerus sordidus SHARP, holotype: (5) habitus; (6) forebody; (7) median dorsal portion of head; (8) median dorsal portion of pronotum; (9) male sternite VIII; (10-11) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 5: 1.0 mm; 6: 0.5 mm; 7-9: 0.2 mm; 10-11: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5326085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5326085/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">8</figureCitation>
). Elytra of variable length. Protarsi apparently without sexual dimorphism, weakly dilated. Metatarsus of variable length; metatarsomeres I-IV of gradually decreasing length; I somewhat longer than II.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF3349658FF4BFA82FE38812E" blockId="1.[178,1085,1350,1401]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Abdomen narrower than elytra; punctation fine, dense on tergites III-VI, somewhat sparser on posterior tergites.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF3349658FF3EFA4DFBD581C9" blockId="1.[178,1084,1416,1467]" box="[199,1084,1416,1438]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">: sternite VII with weakly concave posterior margin, otherwise unmodified; sternite</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF3349658FF4BFA62FD9F81EC" blockId="1.[178,1084,1416,1467]" box="[178,630,1445,1467]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">VIII with relatively small posterior excision.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF334965BFF4BFA0FFEB3857C" blockId="1.[178,1085,1483,1593]" lastBlockId="2.[178,1085,218,299]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="1171" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">
C o m m e n t: In the original description of the genus, 
<bibRefCitation id="197B238BF3349658FD0BFA0FFC9681B6" author="SHARP D" box="[754,895,1483,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170" pagination="537 - 672" refId="ref3630" refString="SHARP D. (1886): Fam. Staphylinidae. - In: Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta, Coleoptera. Vol. 1 (2). - London, Taylor &amp; Francis: 537 - 672." type="book chapter" year="1886">SHARP (1886)</bibRefCitation>
erroneously states that the labrum is &quot;rounded in front, but divided by a deep angular incision almost to the base&quot; and that the mandibles have &quot;feeble teeth&quot;. The shape of the labrum is the only character indicated by 
<bibRefCitation id="197B238BF3349658FE66F9E7FDBB826E" author="CAMERON M" box="[415,594,1571,1593]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170" pagination="160 - 198" refId="ref3446" refString="CAMERON M. (1924): New species of Staphylinidae from India. - The Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1924: 160 - 198." type="journal article" year="1924">CAMERON (1924)</bibRefCitation>
to distinguish 
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F3349658FD16F9E7FCB6826F" box="[751,863,1571,1592]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Neosclerus</emphasis>
from 
<taxonomicName id="BAEA25F9F3349658FC5BF9E7FBEF826F" box="[930,1030,1571,1592]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Eusclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F3349658FC5BF9E7FBEF826F" box="[930,1030,1571,1592]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1170">Eusclerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The erroneous description of the mandibles is evidently based on the condition of the 
<typeStatus id="A251E0D8F337965BFBFEFF1EFF37855A" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="BAEA25F9F337965BFEF3FF3DFE63855A" box="[266,394,248,270]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Eusclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugifrons">
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F337965BFEF3FF3DFE63855A" box="[266,394,248,270]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">E. rugifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the teeth are somewhat reduced as a result of either damage or wear.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF337965BFF4BFEFFFECE8657" blockId="2.[178,1085,314,512]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus is characterised and distinguished from other genera of Medonina resembling 
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F337965BFE6CFE9CFE31853A" box="[405,472,344,365]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">Sunius</emphasis>
particularly by the combination of conspicuously large eyes and a granulosely punctate pronotum. Species of 
<taxonomicName id="BAEA25F9F337965BFD3BFEB1FCC485DD" authorityName="LYNCH" authorityYear="1884" box="[706,813,373,394]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sciocharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F337965BFD3BFEB1FCC485DD" box="[706,813,373,394]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">Sciocharis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with similarly large eyes have a bidentate anterior margin of the labrum, bidentate mandibles, and an antenna of different morphology (antennomeres I-II enlarged and III-XI thin). In 
<emphasis id="4F9E8268F337965BFC64FE74FBE48592" box="[925,1037,432,453]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">Neosclerus</emphasis>
, the punctation of the pronotum is not granulose and the ligula is of different shape and chaetotaxy.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D555E7AF337965BFF4BFDD4FC538672" blockId="2.[178,954,527,549]" box="[178,954,527,549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">
D i v e r s i t y: The genus currently includes two species from 
<collectingCountry id="05FD1EEAF337965BFCBFFDCBFC5E8672" box="[838,951,527,549]" name="Guatemala" pageId="2" pageNumber="1171">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
